snippet.textDisplay:
Finally someone who understands why Americans buy tap water in bottles.

1. Convenience. We love to grab a bottle and go. My family always has a few in the car. On road trip vacations we'll throw a whole case of water in the trunk.

2 Taste, a lot of municipal waters taste like ass. Nearly always perfectly clean and healthy, but the mineral contents can make some taste like an old sock. -

snippet.textDisplay: Well, great for this amazing information. But it's in the past. snippet.textDisplay: Bottled water here in the states or at least here in Vegas is a MASSIVE money maker. You would think our water coming from the tap is brown by the way they buy massive quantities of this stuff. Fact is Vegas from the tap here in Vegas is just fine, clear and clean. Coming from the East and living with well water, it was only natural I would have a filter system in place. I bought this house with its huge filtration system already in place. It came with two very large filers, one carbon and one paper. I was to change them yearly....but I didn't and it was 5 years before I did. The white paper filter was still white, not brown, not gray, but white. That is an indication the water coming into this house is VERY CLEAN. So this crazy thing about buying tons of bottled water to me makes no sense.Bottled water here in the states is a MAJOR money maker...the day I pay $6.00 for a small bottle of flavored tap water will be a cold day in hell.

snippet.textDisplay: I grew up in Wales where the tap water tastes like it's fresh off a mountain, especially in comparison to the water in High Wycombe (which was utterly repulsive). I went through a lot of bottled water. Dasani was marketed hard - in place of all other brands on campus. I bought 1 bottle. Took 1 mouthful. Then loudly declared "that tastes like shitty London water". Took it back got a refund with my friends laughing at me for being a water snob. A couple of weeks later they were no longer laughing!
